Question 1

Who can hold their breath longer on average, those with right or left ocular dominance? Plot the data using ggplot2 to find out. The plots should include error bars (depicting the standard error of the means). Then use the mean() and sd() functions to find mean and standard deviation of the two eye dominance groups.

#Since we are only interested in people with either right or left ocular dominance, I will start by filtering the data, so I only have people with right or left ocular dominance.

filter_ocular_dom <- filter(df, ocular_dom != "Both")

ggplot(filter_ocular_dom, aes(x=ocular_dom, y=breath_hold, fill = ocular_dom)) +
  geom_bar(stat='summary', fun.y = mean, width = 0.5, color="black") +
  geom_errorbar(stat = 'summary', fun.data = mean_se, width = 0.2) +
  labs(x = "Ocular Dominance", y = "Average Breath Hold") +
  theme_minimal() + scale_fill_brewer( palette = "Blues")

summary_breath_byod <- filter_ocular_dom %>% 
  group_by(ocular_dom) %>% 
  summarise(mean(breath_hold), sd(breath_hold),Count=n())
summary_breath_byod
## # A tibble: 2 x 4
##   ocular_dom `mean(breath_hold)` `sd(breath_hold)` Count
##   <fct>                    <dbl>             <dbl> <int>
## 1 Left                      53.4              21.3    21
## 2 Right                     57.7              20.6    37

Explain your results in plain terms here:

Our data tells us, that people with right ocular dominance in our sample can hold their breath longer on average (57.7 seconds) than people in our sample with left ocular dominance (53.4 seconds).

On the graph however we see, that the errorbars, indicating the 95% confidence interval, overlap each other, and from the table we see that the standard diviation - the standard diviation is found column called âsd(breath_hold)â and it tells us something about the variance in the data - the standard diviation is very big.

This all tells us that the difference between the two averages we found are highly likely to be because of random variation within the data we collected.

Question 3

Are the breath_hold data normally distributed? Provide visual and numeric support for your answer.

ggplot(df, aes (x=breath_hold)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), color = "darkblue", fill = "lightblue", binwidth = 3)+
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = mean(df$breath_hold, na.rm = TRUE), sd = sd(df$breath_hold, na.rm = TRUE)), colour = "black", size = 1)

qplot(sample = df$breath_hold)

#do we use describe() or stat.desc()?

describe(df$breath_hold)
##    vars  n  mean    sd median trimmed   mad min max range skew kurtosis
## X1    1 62 55.77 20.58  51.91    54.3 19.27  23 110    87 0.58    -0.36
##      se
## X1 2.61
round(stat.desc(df$breath_hold, basic = F, norm = T), digits = 3)
##       median         mean      SE.mean CI.mean.0.95          var 
##       51.905       55.771        2.613        5.226      423.474 
##      std.dev     coef.var     skewness     skew.2SE     kurtosis 
##       20.578        0.369        0.580        0.954       -0.359 
##     kurt.2SE   normtest.W   normtest.p 
##       -0.299        0.959        0.035

Explain your results in plain terms here:

For the data to be normally distributed the graph of the data should be resemble a bell - it should be symetric, not spiky, not leaning to one side or the other, and decreasing smoothly on both sides of the symetry axis. Data from the real world are never perfectly normal, but the data can be close enough to normally ditributed that we still call it normally distributed.

the kurtosis (the spikiness) and the skew (if the graph is âleaningâ to one side or the other or not leaning at all) would have to have a value of 0. In this instance I found the value of spikiness to be -0.36 and the value of leaniness to be 0.58. These two values are actually not far from a normal distribution, so I would say that the data is normally distrubuted.
